<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sect-subspaces">
  <title>The Span and Basis of a Subspace</title>

  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li>
        Define a subspace of a vector space.
      </li>

      <li>
        Show that a subset is a subspace.
      </li>

      <li>
        Define the span of a set of vectors in a vector space.
      </li>

      <li>
        Show that a set of vectors spans a subspace.
      </li>

      <li>
        Define the basis of a vector space.
      </li>

      <li>
        Find the representation of a vector with respect to a basis.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In <xref ref="sect-linear-comb-span" />, we saw the span of vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
      We now extend this example to the span of any subspace.
      In addition, the notion of a basis  of the subspace is introduced.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-abstract-linear-independence">
    <title>Linear Independence</title>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="sect-linear-independence"/>, the linear independence of vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> were defined and many examples shown.
      We extend this notion to vectors in a general vector space.
    </p>

    <definition xml:id="def-abstract-linear-independence">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S = \left\{\boldsymbol{v}_1, \boldsymbol{v}_2, \ldots \boldsymbol{v}_n\right\}</m> be a set of vectors in a vectors space <m>V</m>.
          The set <m>S</m> is <term>linear independent</term> if for <m>c_1, c_2, \ldots, c_n \in \mathbb{R}</m>, the equation <m>c_1 \boldsymbol{v}_1 + c_2 \boldsymbol{v}_2 + \cdots + c_n \boldsymbol{v}_n = 0</m> implies that <m>c_1 = c_2 = \cdots = c_n = 0</m>.
          If not, then the set is <term>linearly dependent</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example xml:id="ex-abstract-linear-independence">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the set
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            S = \left\{ 1, x, x^2 \right\}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          is linearly independent in <m>{\cal P}_2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          To show this, we need to show that if
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            c_1 (1) + c_2 (x) + c_3 (x^2) = 0
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          then <m>c_1 = c_2 = c_3 = 0</m>.
          Note that the zero on the right hand side is the zero polynomial.
          Thus, equating coefficients, we get the system
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>c_1 \amp = 0 </mrow>
            <mrow>c_2 \amp = 0 </mrow>
            <mrow>c_3 \amp = 0</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          which has the only solution of <m>c_1 = c_2 = c_3 = 0</m>, thus the set is linearly independent.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Are the matrices in the set 
          <me>
            \left\{ \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 
            \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp -1 
            \end{bmatrix}, \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 2 \\ -2 \amp -2 
            \end{bmatrix} \right\}
          </me>
          linearly independent or dependent in <m>{\cal M}_{2 \times 2}</m>? 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To determine this, we need to solve 
          <me>
            c_1 \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 1 \\ 1 \amp 1 
            \end{bmatrix} + c_2  \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp -1 \\ 1 \amp -1 
            \end{bmatrix} + c_3 \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 2 \\ -2 \amp -2 
            \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 
            \end{bmatrix}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          The solution of this is by equating terms or the system:
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}
            c_1 + c_2 + 2c_3 \amp = 0 \\
            c_1 - c_2 + 2c_3 \amp = 0 \\
            c_1 + c_2 - 2c_3 \amp = 0 \\
            c_1 - c_2 - 2c_3 \amp = 0
            \end{aligned}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          This system has the unique solution <m>c_1 = c_2 = c_3 = 0</m>, thus the set is linearly independent.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>


  <subsection xml:id="subsec-subspaces">
    <title>Subspaces</title>

    <p>
      Recall that it is important to understand if a set of vectors is a span of a set or space, because we are able to take a linear combination of the vectors to get any other vector in the set.
      Since we have extended the notion of a vector space, the span will play the same role.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>U</m> be a subset of a vector space <m>V</m>.
          If <m>U</m> is also a vector space, then <m>U</m> is a <term>subspace</term>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      The next three examples show that we have already seen subspaces because we know subsets of known vector spaces that are vector spaces themselves.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We showed in  <xref ref="ex-lines-through-origin-vector-space" /> that the set of all lines in <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> that pass through the origin is a vector space.
          Since the set is a subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>, it is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> as well.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Since <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> is itself a vector space and a subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>, then <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m> is a subspace.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Recall that the set
          <me>
            {\cal P}_2=\{ a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2\; | \; a_0, a_1, a_2 \in \mathbb{R} \}
          </me>
          is the set of all quadratic functions.
        </p>

        <p>
          The set <m>{\cal P}_1 = \{a_0 + a_1 x \; | \; a_0, a_1 \in \mathbb{R} \}</m> of all linear functions is itself a vector space as well as a subset of <m>{\cal P}_2</m>, therefore <m>{\cal P}_1</m> is a subspace of <m>{\cal P}_2</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          In addition, the set <m>\{ a x^2\; | \; a \in \mathbb{R}\}</m> is a vector space as well as a subset of <m>{\cal P}_2</m>, therefore it is a subspace.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The above examples show that there are many already known subspaces.
      There are many cases though that aren't evident or to show it is a subspace, we would need to prove all 10 properties that it is a vector space.
      The next lemma, however, shows that isn't the case.
    </p>

    <lemma xml:id="lemma-subspace" >
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>S</m> be a nonempty subset <m>S</m> of a vector space <m>V</m>, under the inherited operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication.
          If for all <m>\boldsymbol{s}_1, \boldsymbol{s}_2 \in S</m> and <m>r_1, r_2 \in \mathbb{R}</m>,
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            r_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + r_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 \in S
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          then <m>S</m> is a subspace.
        </p>
      </statement>


      <proof>
        <p>
          This means that if <m>S</m> is a subset of <m>V</m>, a vector space, to prove that <m>S</m> is a subspace, we only need to check if <m>r_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + r_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 \in S</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>S</m> is a subspace of <m>V</m>, properties (2), (3), (5) and (7)-(10) of <xref ref="def-vector-space" /> hold for <m>S</m>.
          Thus we only need to prove closure under addition and scalar multiplication as well as the existence of the identity element.
        </p>

        <p>
          Property 1:  Because <m>r_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + r_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 \in S</m>, let <m>r_1=r_2=1</m>, thus <m>\boldsymbol{s}_1+\boldsymbol{s}_2 \in S</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Property 4: If <m>r_1=0</m> and <m>r_2=0</m>, then this shows that <m>\boldsymbol{0} \in S</m>, so there is an identity element.
        </p>

        <p>
          Property 6: Because <m>r_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + r_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 \in S</m>, let <m>r_2=0</m>, thus <m>r_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 \in S</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>

    <p>
      We will use this definition to prove that certain sets are subspaces.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            V = \left\{ \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix} \; | \; v_2 = k v_1 \right\}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          (that is, all vectors on a line of slope <m>k</m>) is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We will use <xref ref="lemma-subspace" />.
          Let
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\boldsymbol{u} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} u_1 \\ u_2 \end{bmatrix} \amp \boldsymbol{v} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ v_2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          be elements of <m>V</m>.
          That is <m>v_2 = k v_1</m> and <m>u_2 = ku_1</m>.
          Then
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>r_1 \boldsymbol{u} + r_2 \boldsymbol{v} \amp = r_1 \begin{bmatrix} u_1 \\ k u_1 \end{bmatrix} + r_2 \begin{bmatrix} v_1 \\ k v_1 \end{bmatrix} =  \begin{bmatrix} r_1 u_1 + r_2 v_1 \\ r_1 k u_1 + r_2 k v_1 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} r_1 u_1 + r_2 v_1 \\ k (r_1 u_1 + r_2 v_1) \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          which is an element of <m>V</m> because the second component is <m>k</m> times the first one.
          Thus <m>V</m> is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^2</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eq-example-diag-matrix">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show using <xref ref="lemma-subspace" /> that
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            V =\left\{ \begin{bmatrix} a \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp b \end{bmatrix} \; | \; a,b \in \mathbb{R} \right\}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          the set of all diagonal matrices is a subspace of <m>{\cal M}_{2 \times 2}</m>, the vector space of all <m>2 \times 2</m> matrices.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          In this case, if we show that for any two matrices
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>A \amp = \begin{bmatrix} a_1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp b_1 \end{bmatrix}, \amp B \amp = \begin{bmatrix} a_2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp b_2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          and scalars <m>r_1, r_2 \in \mathbb{R}</m> that  <m>r_1 A + r_2 B</m> is in the set.
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>r_1 A + r_2 B \amp = r_1 \begin{bmatrix} a_1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp b_1 \end{bmatrix}+ r_2 \begin{bmatrix} a_2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp b_2 \end{bmatrix} </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \begin{bmatrix} r_1 a_1 + r_2 a_2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp r_1 b_1 + r_2 b_2 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          which is a diagonal matrix, therefore in <m>V</m>, thus this is a subspace.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
      In <xref ref="sect-row-col-space-rank"/>, we explored the <term>null space</term> of a matrix.
      In the next lemma, we show that any null space is a subspace.
    </p>

    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m</m> by <m>n</m> matrix.
          The null space of <m>A</m> is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>


      <proof>
        <p>
          We will use <xref ref="lemma-subspace" /> to solve this.
          Let both <m>\boldsymbol{x}</m> and <m>\boldsymbol{y}</m> be in the null space of <m>A</m>.
          This means that <m>A\boldsymbol{x}=\boldsymbol{0}</m> and <m>A\boldsymbol{y}=\boldsymbol{0}</m>.
          We need to show that <m>r_1 \boldsymbol{x} + r_2 \boldsymbol{y}</m> is in the null space of <m>A</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>A(r_1 \boldsymbol{x} + r_2 \boldsymbol{y}) \amp = r_1 A\boldsymbol{x} + r_2 A\boldsymbol{y} </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = r_1 (\boldsymbol{0}) + r_2 (\boldsymbol{0}) = \boldsymbol{0}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Vectors in the null space are vectors of length <m>n</m>, so the null space is a subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> and since  <m>r_1 \boldsymbol{x} + r_2 \boldsymbol{y}</m> is in the null space of <m>A</m>, then the null space is a subspace of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>

    <p>
      This is an important result that we will see in eigenvalues in the next chapter.
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <subsection>
    <title>The Span of a set of vectors</title>

    <p>
      We saw in  <xref ref="sect-linear-comb-span" /> the span of a set of vectors in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
      We now generalize this to any vector space.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <term>span</term> of a nonempty subset <m>S=\{\boldsymbol{s}_1, \boldsymbol{s}_2, \ldots, \boldsymbol{s}_n\}</m> of a vector space is the set of all linear combinations of the vectors in <m>S</m>.
          That is,
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            \text{span}(S) = \{ c_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + c_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 + \cdots + c_n \boldsymbol{s}_n\; | \; \text{$c_1, c_2, \ldots, c_n \in \mathbb{R}, \boldsymbol{s}_1, \boldsymbol{s}_2, \ldots, \boldsymbol{s}_n \in S$} \}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      To show that a subset of vectors span a subspace <m>S</m>, we need to show that any vector in <m>S</m> can be written as a linear combination of the spanning vectors.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the set <m>\{2+x,1,x+x^2\}</m> spans <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          In this case, we need show that a general polynomial in <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m> can be written as a linear combination of elements of the given set.
          That is
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            c_1 (2+x) + c_2 (1) + c_3 (x+x^2) = a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          and if there is a solution for the <m>c</m>'s, then that shows the the set spans <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m>.
          To find the solution, use the technique of equating coefficients.
          Write down the coefficients for the constant terms, <m>x</m> terms and <m>x^2</m> terms respectively.
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>2 c_1 + c_2 \amp = a_0 </mrow>
            <mrow>c_1 + c_3 \amp = a_1 </mrow>
            <mrow>c_3 \amp = a_2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          This has a solution <m>c_3=a_2, c_1 = a_1-a_2</m> and <m>c_2 = a_0 - 2(a_1-a_2)</m>, which means that a linear combination of the three <q>vectors</q> can form any quadratic function, thus the given set spans <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <lemma>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The span of any subset of a vector space is a subspace.
        </p>
      </statement>


      <proof>
        <p>
          Let <m>S</m> be the subset and <m>\boldsymbol{s}_1, \boldsymbol{s}_2, \ldots, \boldsymbol{s}_n</m> be the elements of <m>S</m>.
          Using <xref ref="lemma-subspace" />, we need to check that <m>\text{span}(S)</m> is closed under linear combinations.
          Let
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\boldsymbol{v} \amp = c_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + c_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 + \cdots + c_n \boldsymbol{s}_n, </mrow>
            <mrow>\boldsymbol{w} \amp = k_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + k_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 + \cdots + k_n \boldsymbol{s}_n</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          then
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>r_1 \boldsymbol{v} + r_2 \boldsymbol{w} \amp = r_1 (c_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + c_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 + \cdots + c_n \boldsymbol{s}_n) + r_2 (k_1 \boldsymbol{s}_1 + k_2 \boldsymbol{s}_2 + \cdots + k_n \boldsymbol{s}_n) </mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = (r_1 c_1 + r_2 k_1) \boldsymbol{s}_1 + (r_1c_2 + r_2 k_2) \boldsymbol{s}_2 + \cdots + (r_1 c_n + r_2 k_n) \boldsymbol{s}_n</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Since this shows that <m>r_1 \boldsymbol{v} + r_2 \boldsymbol{w}</m> is in <m>S</m>, then <m>S</m> is a subspace.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </lemma>

    <p>
      This lemma allows us to talk about a vector space in terms of the vectors that span it.
      For example, instead of thinking of <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m>,we think of the span of <m>\{2+x,1,x+x^2\}</m> (in this case, it may not be more helpful, but other cases it is).
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Show that the following vectors span <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>:
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\boldsymbol{e}_1 \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \amp \boldsymbol{e}_2 \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{bmatrix}, \amp \boldsymbol{e}_3 \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          Because the vector <m>\boldsymbol{x}=[x_1,x_2,x_3]^{\intercal}</m> can be written <m>\boldsymbol{x}=x_1 \boldsymbol{e}_1 + x_2 \boldsymbol{e}_2 + x_3 \boldsymbol{e}_3</m>, then these vectors span <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Does <m>\{2+x,x^2 \}</m> span <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          To determine this, we will try write a general polynomial in <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m>,
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          as a linear combination of the set of vectors or
        </p>

        <p>
          <me>
            a_0 + a_1 x + a_2 x^2 = c_1 (2+x) + c_2 x^2
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          and equating coefficients,
        </p>

        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>a_0 \amp = 2c_1  </mrow>
            <mrow>a_1 \amp = c_1 </mrow>
            <mrow>a_2 \amp = c_2</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          There's no solution to this because <m>c_1</m> can't simultaneously equal <m>a_1</m> and <m>a_0/2</m>, so  <m>\{2+x,x^2\}</m> does not span <m>\mathcal{P}_2</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>



</section>